Made in collaboration with [Olivia Tai](https://oliviatai.com/)
&nbsp;
Caddisfly larvae protect their newborn bodies in a portable nest of local debris: stones, shells, twigs, forgotten plastic. These insects encase themselves in the world around them, a visual representation of their place of origin and belonging. Trained on the entire Internet, modern AI, in the form of LLMs, also carries with it the leftover lives of other beings. 
&nbsp;
A(I) STICK pokes at the assumption that an AI device needs to be a sleek, omniscient, constant companion. A(I) STICK does not sit in your pocket, but instead rests in a nest of its own, talking when you pick it up.  What does a stick offer that our pursuit of superintelligence misses out on? What other intelligences might we find if we tried to listen to them? The future need not be intelligent; the future can just be a stick.
